    <title>Combined summary - An Argument For Single-Asset Lightning Network</title>
    <updated>2023-06-02T16:36:51.857666+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2018-December/001755.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Lightning Network is facing technical barriers in implementing seamless currency conversions due to the creation of premium-free American Call Options through the use of hashlocked timelocked contracts (HTLCs). This poses a significant problem for exchange nodes as they may lose funds due to tied-up liquidity. The writer suggests solutions such as requiring payment for setting up HTLCs, increasing exchange node fees, or limiting the timelock of cross-asset swaps. However, each solution has its drawbacks. The possibility of creating a cryptographic protocol for atomically swapping information to address this issue is also highlighted.Tamas Blummer discusses exchanges making offers with an exchange rate between assets that compensates them for the cost they incur by making the offer. However, ZmnSCPxj points out the risk of rational entities exploiting premium-free options, leading to a preference for a single asset across the network and making multi-asset Lightning Networks economically unviable.Experts compare decentralized exchange systems to centralized exchanges. Although high fees may be charged by trusted third parties in a decentralized system, it is still considered an improvement over the current situation. This proposal is regarded as more competitive since smaller companies can participate due to lower trust requirements and users can switch between multiple RM parties easily. Furthermore, the damage that can be done by an RM to trading parties is less compared to what a centralized exchange can do by stealing deposited funds.The writer suggests that misbehaving RMs can be punished but doubts its feasibility. Despite this, they believe that the potential for a decentralized exchange system is significant, especially considering its potential to increase market competition and give users more control. Therefore, the ability to remain flexible and open to different options will be important moving forward, as the adoption of this system could have far-reaching consequences.</summary>
